This approach leverages the fact that for n = 8, we can explicitly construct a coloring that avoids any three points (i, j, 2j - i) being the same color. The proof proceeds by checking all possible i and j values and confirming that no such triplet exists in the given coloring. 

This approach is not optimal in terms of computational complexity, but it works because the number of cases is small (i and j range from 1 to 8). For larger n, we would need a more abstract approach. 

